<DOC><DOCNO> AP880803-0173 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1549EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-GulfRdp     08-03 0552</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Gulf Rdp,0568</SECOND><HEAD>Iran Accuses Iraq Of Using Chemical Weapons Again</HEAD><BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Iran said Wednesday an Iraqi chemicalbomb attack wounded more than 1,000 civilians, and Tehran calledfor a ban on the export of materials used in the weapons.   The official Islamic Republic News Agency also reported thatIranian anti-aircraft batteries shot down an Iraqi jet fighter thatattacked an industrial plant on Wednesday near the southern city ofBushehr.   Iraqi warplanes also attacked an industrial target in thewestern province of Khuzestan, the news agency reported indispatches monitored in Cyprus.   It said both targets were damaged in the Iraqi attacks, but nocasualties were reported. It gave no further details on the targets.   Iraq said it attacked an Iranian oil-pumping station and anatural-gas facility, in a war communique carried by the officialIraqi News Agency.   The communique denied that an Iraqi jet was downed. Both newsagencies were monitored in Nicosia. Their contents could not beindependently verified.   Peace talks aimed at reaching agreement on a cease-fire based onU.N. Security Council Resolution 598 made little headway Wednesday,with Iraq continuing to insist on face-to-face talks, which Iranhas refused.   At the United Nations, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellarcontinued efforts to break the deadlock over Iraq's demand.   He did not schedule formal meetings with Iranian or Iraqiofficials. But aides said contacts with both sides were continuing.The talks began July 27.   In the Gulf of Oman, a small cargo vessel exploded and sank onWednesday, but the blast appeared to be caused by an explosion onboard and not a mine, gulf-based shipping executives said. Noserious injuries were reported.   The Greek captain and eight Asian seamen aboard the 1,870-tonFatima were rescued by helicopters from a French missile destroyer.The executives said heat in the area may have caused the vessel'scargo of gas bottles to explode.   In Paris, the son of the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi issuedan appeal on Wednesday calling on his countrymen to overthrowAyatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's ``reign of darkness'' in Iran.   IRNA said 1,031 civilians in the northern province of WestAzerbaijan were wounded on Tuesday when Iraqi warplanes droppedchemical bombs on the town of Oshanaviyeh. It said most victimswere treated for minor injuries.   In an interview with Iranian television from the United Nations,Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati called on Tuesday for a ban onthe export of materials used to manufacture chemical weapons.   Velayati was reacting to a U.N. report released Monday thatdocumented massive use of outlawed chemical weapons by Iraq.Velayati's remarks were carried by Tehran Radio on Wednesday.   The late shah's son, who calls himself Reza Shah II, invitedIranians of all walks of life to partake in the establishment of``popular government.''   He cited ``the impotence of the Islamic republic to bringhonorable peace and reconstruction, noting the imminent collapse ofthe reign of darkness.''   ``In this life and death struggle for democracy my destiny isintertwined with yours ... the time is now to break your silence,''said Reza Shah, who has some support among exiled Iranians. Hisremarks were released in Paris, where his monarchist movement isbased, on the occasion of the anniversary of the defunct royalconstitution.</TEXT></DOC>